  "slug": "banoffee-cheesecake",
  "title": "Banoffee cheesecake",
  "subtitle": "No-bake, biscuit base with dulce de leche and banana",
  "excerpt": "A fridge-set cheesecake with a digestive biscuit base, a cream cheese and double cream filling with dulce de leche folded through, and banana and cream on top. No gelatine, no oven.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Banoffee pie was created at The Hungry Monk restaurant in Sussex in 1972. The cheesecake variant is a domestic adaptation: the pastry base becomes a biscuit base, the condensed-milk toffee stays, and the cream filling incorporates cream cheese for stability. This version follows the standard British domestic formula for no-bake cheesecake.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A no-bake cheesecake works on one idea. Whipped double cream folded into cream cheese sets the filling firm in the fridge, with no gelatine needed. Whip the cream to soft peaks, not stiff. Over-whipped cream folds in lumpy and the cheesecake sets with a grainy bite.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "dulce de leche",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpaeewv60000h0v4wauny73y"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " goes into the filling as a swirl rather than a thorough mix, which gives a ripple effect when the cheesecake is cut. Add the banana to the top no more than 2 hours before serving; it will brown if it sits longer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
